ehavior.\n\nFor behavior 3, mocking downstream services masks whether the handler truly executes in parallel or waits for them. Even if static analysis catches an `await`, the runtime behavior of returning quickly while work continues asynchronously needs real execution to verify.\n\nBehavior 4 requires testing against actual queue latency to confirm the 3-second SLA holds. Mocking eliminates the real timing constraints that would expose violations.\n\nBehavior 5 needs a genuine persistent store for idempotency—a mocked Set won't reveal database slowness or reliability issues that could allow duplicates in production.\n\nBehavior 7 demands a real queue to test whether capacity limits actually prevent overflow, since mocks can be configured to never fill.\n\nFor unit tests, behavior 1 (signature validation) is a pure function where the logic either correctly implements HMAC-SHA256 or it doesn't. The validation itself can be tested in isolation without external dependencies.\n\nBehavior 6 (503 on full queue) focuses on the handler's error handling—whether it properly catches QueueFullError and returns the right status code. Mocking the queue to throw that error is the right approach here, since I'm testing the handler's response logic, not the queue's actual capacity enforcement.\n\nNow I should verify the test descriptions actually match what I'm claiming. The signature validation test calls validate_signature() with a mismatched signature and confirms it returns 401 without calling enqueue—that's a solid unit test. The queue-before-response test requires a real queue and checks that an event persists after the HTTP response completes, which properly captures the ordering requirement. The handler-returns-without-waiting test measures response time with a slow downstream service to confirm the response comes back quickly, independent of downstream latency.\n\nFor the concurrent requests test, I'm verifying the 3-second SLA holds even under load with multiple slow down